1480":"1480","Abt 1390":"circa 1390","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","Langley, Kent, England":"Langley, Kent, England"},"en":{"Abt 1390–Bef 1480":"about 1390–before 1480","1390–1480":"1390–1480","1433–1490":"1433–1490","Bef 1480":"before 1480","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","Abt 1433":"about 1433","1480":"1480","Abt 1390":"about 1390","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","Langley, Kent, England":"Langley, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wolston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Woolston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Woolston","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wol(f)stan</i> (Old English <i>Wulfstān</i>, composed of the elements <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’ + <i>stān</i> stone).","habitational name from Wolston (Warwickshire), Woolstone (Buckinghamshire), or any of various places called Woolston, such as Woolston in West Alvington (Devon), Woolston in Warrington (Lancashire), and Woolston Hall in Chigwell (Essex). The Warwickshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfrīc</i> (genitive <i>Wulfrīces</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Buckinghamshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfsige</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Devon placename probably has the same etymology as the Buckinghamshire placename. The Lancashire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulf</i> (genitive <i>Wulfes</i>) + <i>tūn</i>. The Essex placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfhelm</i> (genitive <i>Wulfhelmes</i>) + <i>tūn</i>. There may have been some confusion with   Wollaston  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":65,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Wolston was born about 1390, in Huntingdonshire, England. He married Margaret Tamworth in 1444, in Langley, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 1480, in Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1390–Bef 1480":"umbes 1390–enne 1480","1390–1480":"1390–1480","1433–1490":"1433–1490","Bef 1480":"enne 1480","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","Abt 1433":"umbes 1433","1480":"1480","Abt 1390":"umbes 1390","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","Huntingdonshire,